## Summary

Uptime Kuma provides a comprehensive monitoring solution with two primary integration methods: REST APIs for external systems and public access, and WebSocket APIs for real-time authenticated operations. The REST API is ideal for embedding status badges on websites, enabling push-based monitoring from external services, and providing public status page access. These endpoints support monitoring visualization through SVG badges showing real-time status, uptime percentages, response times, and certificate expiration. The push API enables external applications and scripts to report their own status to Uptime Kuma, making it adaptable to custom monitoring scenarios beyond the built-in monitor types.

The WebSocket API serves as the primary interface for administration and real-time monitoring operations, supporting complete CRUD operations for monitors, notifications, tags, maintenance windows, and status pages. It enables real-time heartbeat streaming, immediate status updates, and live dashboard synchronization. Integration patterns include embedding public status badges on company websites, creating custom monitoring dashboards with real-time WebSocket connections, implementing automated maintenance window management through scheduled tasks, building notification workflows that integrate with existing incident management systems, and developing custom monitoring agents that push status to Uptime Kuma via the REST push API. The modular architecture allows extending functionality through custom monitor types, notification providers, and monitor condition evaluation logic.
